David Lynch hints at that idea in Twin Peaks about nuclear explosions opening portals to the demonic realm, but really any aerial bombing is the same. In some circles Dresden being a mass human sacrifice to open doors for certain dark forces to enter is taken as an ordinary fact.

D. Galkovsky is a master at this, he takes Orwell's 1984 which is almost the definition of banality today and just starts chopping at random small details, how a character who turns out not to exist's Jewish name alludes to James Burnham being an American intelligence agent, etc.

The best way to avoid inanities and clichees is to always avoid generalizations and stick to very particular details when it comes to authors. Just throwing the word Faustian around gets old, but Spengler's quote about brown light being outside of Nature's capabilities is elating
